To all, <br><br>
I am both impressed with both the question and Anne's response.<br><br>
Last summer a playground was built in the town where I live.  The project was started by a veteran of WWII.  He was at the Battle of the Bulge.  The local Kiwaniis spearheaded the project.  Over $100,000 was raised during a two year period before construction.  The playground was built in five days with 2000 volunteers.  Everyone in town was/is proud of their efforts.  I, personally, had a great time with my efforts on the project.  Something for the kids brought the community together  It was like an old fashioned barn building.<br><br>
In response to the above query I can only say that media is fueled by drama.  There is a lot of money to be made in books, movies and television.  Conflict, pain, suffering, resurgence, heroism etc. are necessary for revenue.  It is that simple.<br><br>
Not so many years ago when there was Post Office shooting, or the like, the papers would say that so and so was a veteran.  That assertion helped to create an image.  I remember reading about random shootings and wondering if the 40 year old was a veteran or not.  That's sad but true.<br><br>
I think that we need to take a look at how we and the media make money.  Recreating some of the negative aspects of our image will take time, and in the eyes of some it may never happen.<br><br>
I know if I wanted to &quot;recruit&quot; money for a project I would have to show a need.  Statistics (and I'm not impressed by them) are necessary in requesting funds.  We live in the information age; which can, more times than not, place more value on perception that &quot;truth.&quot;<br><br>
Paul
